  "doc_id": "39246",
  "text": "A number of other stressors have been shown to elicit opiate system responses. Administration of ether increased pituitary 3endorphin immunoreactivity [CITATION_1] , and chronic seizures stimulated the biosynthesis of POMC and POMC mRNA in the pituitary [CITATION_2] . Injection of hypertonic saline raised proenkephalin A mRNA in the paraventricular nucleus of the rat (205). Chronic exposure to weak magnetic fields or to naloxone produced hypoalgesia in snails (Cepaea nernoralis), consistent with either a facilitation of aversive conditioning and/or antagonism of the excitatory, hyperalgesic effects of low amounts of endogenous opiates [CITATION_3] . In humans, the stress of a difficult task or perceived failure increased rather than decreased reports of pain to cold, although it was not clear whether the effect was due to a change in reporting or in sensitivity to the aversive stimuli [CITATION_4] . The involvement of the endogenous opiate system was also not delineated.",
